     And I promise, we'll keep it practical and fun—
    <prosody rate="-8%">
      no PhD required.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    Perfect.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      So where do we start?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      OK, so imagine skiing as a <emphasis>three-legged stool</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
     Each leg represents one of the three core skills:
     <emphasis level="moderate">Pressure Control</emphasis>,
     <emphasis level="moderate">Rotational Control</emphasis>,
     and <emphasis level="moderate">Edging Control</emphasis>.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    Take away any one of these, and the whole thing collapses.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    A three-legged stool—I like that visual.
     <prosody pitch="+6%">
      So these three skills support everything?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <emphasis level="strong">Everything.</emphasis>
     Whether you're making gentle cruising turns on a groomed run
    or charging down a black diamond, you're using these three skills.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    The difference between a beginner and an expert is just
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      how skillfully they blend them together.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    OK, so let's break them down one by one.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      What's the first pillar?
    </prosody>
      <break time="350ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Pressure Control Section -->
  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="newscast">
      The first pillar is <emphasis level="strong">Pressure Control</emphasis>.
    </mstts:express-as>
     This is all about managing the forces between you and the snow.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    And here's the thing—when you turn, the snow isn't just sitting there passively.
     <prosody rate="+3%">
      It's pushing back on you, sometimes with a force that's
      <emphasis level="strong">twice your body weight</emphasis>!
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <mstts:express-as style="excited">
      <prosody pitch="+15%">
        Twice my body weight?
      </prosody>
       That's wild!
    </mstts:express-as>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.0">
      Right?
    </mstts:express-as>
     So pressure control is about managing that force in three different ways.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      First, you need to control where the pressure sits along the length of your ski—
      that's <emphasis>fore-aft pressure</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
     <prosody pitch="+3%">
      Are you pressuring the tip, the middle, or the tail?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+10%">
      And that matters because...?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-8%">
      Because your ski is shaped like an hourglass, right?
       That curve is called the <emphasis>sidecut</emphasis>.
       When you flex the ski properly along its entire length,
      that sidecut engages with the snow and carves a clean arc.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    But if your weight slips back even a little, you lose the tip—
     the ski flattens out, and you start skidding instead of carving.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    Ah, the dreaded skid.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      So how do we stay forward without, like, falling over our tips?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Three-Joint System -->
  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="friendly">
      Great question.
    </mstts:express-as>
     This is where it gets interesting.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      Your body has three major joints that control fore-aft pressure:
       your <emphasis>ankles</emphasis>,
       your <emphasis>knees</emphasis>,
       and your <emphasis>hips</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="+3%">
      And here's the kicker—they sometimes work in <emphasis>opposition</emphasis> to each other.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+10%">
      Opposition? What do you mean?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    OK, let's start simple.
     <prosody rate="-10%">
      Imagine your ski is a seesaw, and your boot is the fulcrum right in the middle.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      If you flex your ankle—you know, push your shin gently into the front of the boot—
       your center of mass moves forward, and the tip of the seesaw presses down.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    So ankle flexion equals forward pressure.
     That makes sense.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    Exactly.
     <prosody pitch="+5%">
      But now here's the paradox:
    </prosody>
     <prosody rate="-8%">
      if you bend your knees—like really bend them, bringing your heels up toward your glutes—
       your center of mass <emphasis level="strong">actually moves backward</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <mstts:express-as style="surprised">
      <prosody pitch="+18%">
        Wait, what?
      </prosody>
       <prosody pitch="+12%">
        So "bend your knees" actually sends my weight back?
      </prosody>
    </mstts:express-as>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="0.9">
      <emphasis level="strong">Exactly!</emphasis>
    </mstts:express-as>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      That's why "bend your knees" is maybe the <emphasis>worst advice</emphasis> in skiing
      if it's not qualified.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    If a beginner tries to get forward just by bending their knees deeply,
     without also flexing their ankles and hinging at the hips,
     they end up sitting back.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="+5%">
      In the backseat!
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    In the backseat.
     <emphasis>Every time.</emphasis>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    OK, so what about the hips?
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      The hips are the <emphasis level="strong">big engine</emphasis>.
       If you hinge forward at the hips—
      like you're taking a slow, controlled bow with a flat back—
       you move your center of mass significantly forward.
       That drives major pressure onto the tip.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    But if you extend your hips, like you're "standing up,"
     your weight moves back toward the center or even the tail.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      So it's like an orchestra—all three joints have to work together perfectly.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.0">
      Exactly.
    </mstts:express-as>
     <prosody rate="-8%">
      The ankle is your <emphasis>fine-tuner</emphasis> for the tip.
       The hip is the <emphasis>master switch</emphasis> for your overall stance.
       And the knee is the <emphasis>dynamic controller</emphasis>
      for absorbing and releasing pressure throughout the turn.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    They all have to be perfectly choreographed.
      <break time="350ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Lateral Pressure -->
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    OK, so we've covered pressure along the length of the ski.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      What about side to side—from one ski to the other?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="friendly">
      Ah, yes.
    </mstts:express-as>
     The second dimension of pressure control.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%" pitch="+3%">
      Here's the golden rule: in a carved turn,
      about <emphasis level="strong">80 percent</emphasis> of your weight
      should be on your outside ski.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <mstts:express-as style="surprised">
      <prosody pitch="+15%">
        Eighty percent?
      </prosody>
       <prosody pitch="+8%">
        So the inside ski is basically just... there?
      </prosody>
    </mstts:express-as>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    It's there, but it's much lighter.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-8%">
      And to make this happen, you need two coordinated movements.
       First, your inside leg has to get shorter—
       you flex the knee and hip more on the inside leg.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      So I'm kind of collapsing on the inside?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    Well, "collapsing" sounds bad.
     <prosody rate="-5%">
      Think of it more like your inside leg is <emphasis>actively shortening</emphasis>
      to allow your body to tip into the turn.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    But—and this is critical—
     <emphasis level="strong">both of your ankles stay equally flexed</emphasis>.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      Why is that important?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    Because if you straighten your inside ankle,
    your fore-aft balance goes out the window.
     You'll end up in the backseat again.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="+5%">
      Everything comes back to that backseat, doesn't it?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="0.9">
      <prosody pitch="+8%">
        It really does!
      </prosody>
    </mstts:express-as>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    Now, here's the second movement, and it's counterintuitive:
     <prosody rate="-8%">
      while your legs are tipping into the turn,
      your upper body—your torso—
      has to tilt <emphasis>toward the outside ski</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <mstts:express-as style="surprised">
      <prosody pitch="+12%">
        Wait, hold on.
      </prosody>
       I always thought you lean your chest into the turn to start it.
       <prosody pitch="+10%">
        Why would you tilt toward the outside ski?
         That feels like you're tilting uphill!
      </prosody>
    </mstts:express-as>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="friendly">
      I know it feels weird!
    </mstts:express-as>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-10%">
      But here's the thing: your legs are already tipping into the turn.
       If your upper body just followed them,
      you'd collapse inward and lose that outside edge completely.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      By tilting your upper body out and downhill,
      you create a counterbalance—
       that's called <emphasis>angulation</emphasis>—
       and that keeps the maximum pressure on that outside ski
      so it can carve cleanly.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      It's like a fighter jet banking into a turn.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.1">
      <prosody pitch="+10%">
        Yes!
      </prosody>
       Perfect analogy.
    </mstts:express-as>
     The wings tip radically, but the cockpit stays oriented and stable.
      <break time="350ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Force Magnitude -->
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    OK, we've covered fore-aft and side-to-side.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      What's the third dimension?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      The third dimension is regulating the <emphasis>magnitude</emphasis> of the force—
       basically, how much pressure you're creating throughout the turn.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      And how do we do that?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-8%">
      Imagine you're on a trampoline.
       You're bouncing softly, but you're trying not to get launched into the air.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      You wouldn't just stand there stiff as a board, right?
       You'd constantly be flexing and extending your knees and hips
      to absorb the force.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      So I'm absorbing the peaks of the force by flexing,
       and then extending to generate new force when I need it.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.0">
      <emphasis level="strong">Exactly!</emphasis>
    </mstts:express-as>
     That's how you keep the skis glued to the snow.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    It stops that jittery, out-of-control feeling you get
    when you try to muscle a turn by being too rigid.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      Absorbing versus resisting.
       That's a huge distinction.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    It really is.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      And here's the key: <emphasis>timing is everything</emphasis>.
       You want to compress—flex your knees and hips—
      right as the force peaks, usually near the fall line.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      Then you extend smoothly as the turn finishes to set up the next one.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    So it's like a suspension system on a car.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.0">
      Or a mountain bike!
    </mstts:express-as>
     You let your legs actively compress to absorb the energy.
     You don't stiffen and lock your knees.
      <break time="700ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Rotational Control Section -->
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    OK, so we've got pressure under control.
     <prosody pitch="+8%">
      Now we need to point the skis where we want to go, right?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="1.0">
      Exactly.
    </mstts:express-as>
     <mstts:express-as style="newscast">
      That's our second pillar: <emphasis level="strong">Rotational Control</emphasis>.
    </mstts:express-as>
     This is all about steering.
     And the key word here is <emphasis>separation</emphasis>.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+10%">
      Separation of what?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-8%">
      Separation of your <emphasis>lower body</emphasis> from your <emphasis>upper body</emphasis>.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      The ideal is <emphasis>leg rotation</emphasis>—
       meaning the legs are moving independently inside the hip socket,
      controlling the direction of the skis,
       while your upper body stays quiet and stable.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+6%">
      So the legs are the engine for turning, and the upper body just... hangs out?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    Well, it's not just hanging out—
     it's providing that crucial counterbalance we talked about earlier.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    But yes, the legs do the steering work.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      Why is that so much better than just twisting my whole body into the turn?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      It all comes down to <emphasis>precision</emphasis>.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      When you steer with your legs, you control everything:
       the duration,
       the amount,
       the rate,
       the speed of the turn—
       with surgical precision.
    </prosody>
    <break time="350ms"/>
    And you can control each ski independently,
    which is huge for adapting to terrain.
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody rate="-3%">
      I remember when I was learning, I'd throw my shoulders downhill,
       thinking "where my shoulders go, the skis will follow."
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="friendly">
      Classic pitfall!
    </mstts:express-as>
     <prosody rate="-8%">
      That's <emphasis>upper body rotation</emphasis>.
       When you lead with your torso—your shoulders, your head—
       the legs are just passively following along.
      <break time="350ms"/>
      And it's almost impossible to control the outcome.
       You get this really abrupt start to the turn that's hard to stop.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      And the inside ski starts turning first, right?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    Often, yes.
     Which just destroys the pressure application we were just talking about.
    <break time="350ms"/>
    <prosody rate="-5%">
      So the rule is simple:
      <emphasis>keep the core calm, let the legs do the work</emphasis>.
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>
  <!-- Tray of Drinks Drill -->
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+21%">
    That sounds simple in theory, but
    <prosody pitch="+8%">
      how do you actually teach someone to do that?
    </prosody>
       </prosody>
  </voice>

  <voice name="en-US-GuyNeural">
    <prosody rate="+23%">
    <mstts:express-as style="cheerful" styledegree="0.9">
